                    },
                    "company": "University of Amsterdam",
                    "description": "During my first internship as a MSc student in Biological Sciences, I investigated population structure of marine mussels (Brachidontes spp) and snails (Nerita spp) in Indonesian marine lakes. This project taught me the basics of phylogenetics, population genetics and geometric morphometric analysis, as well as molecular lab techniques such as DNA extraction, PCR amplification and sequencing. During my eight month internship I was supervised by dr. Katja Peijnenburg and dr. Lisa Becking. The results have lead to a paper that has been published in PeerJ:\n\nBecking, L.E., de Leeuw, C.A., Knegt, B., Maas, D.L., de Voogd, N.J., Abdunnur, Suyatna, I., Peijnenburg, K.T.C.A. (2016) Highly divergent mussel lineages in isolated Indonesian marine lakes. PeerJ 4:e249.\nLink: https://peerj.com/articles/2496/",
                    "title": "MSc internship",
                    "employment_type": null
                },
                {
                    "location": "Science Park, Amsterdam",
                    "date": {
                        "start": {
                            "month": 12,
                            "day": null,
                            "year": 2010
                        },
                        "end": {
                            "month": 3,
                            "day": null,
                            "year": 2011
                        }
                    },
                    "company": "University of Amsterdam",
                    "description": "As the first in a series of larger research projects to be conducted for the MSc curriculum Biological Sciences, I engaged into a literature review of the Handicap Principle, a much-debated topic in evolutionary biology, explaining the occurance of seemingly maladaptive traits. The idea was first instigated by Amotz Zahavi in 1975, and states that by demonstrating extravagant and costly traits, males can try to impress females, in an attempt to convince them to mate. This theory has led to an extensive amount of scientific discussion, heated debates, mathematical modeling, and observational studies. In my review, I summarize the onset of this discussion (1975) until the first synthesis was reached between the Handicap Principle and its main adversary, Runaway Sexual Selection, by Hanna Kokko in 2006. Specifically, from a set of theoretical papers on this subject, I derive the criteria that an emperical study of the Handicap Principle should meet.\nThis project was supervised by prof. Maurice W. Sabelis.\n\nProject title:\nThe Handicap Principle \u2013 selection for viability",
                    "title": "MSc literature review",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
